\section{Discussion}

\begin{frame}{Discussion}
\begin{itemize}
    \item\small The relationship between FCOVER and NDVI depends on several factors (vegetation type, canopy structure, environmental conditions...), but it's generally a positive correlation. This is because healthier and denser vegetation (higher NDVI values) often results in a greater Fcover.
    \item\small Both NDVI and FCOVER analysis suggests that, in the area considered, the \textbf{vegetation is in a better condition than before}.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Discussion}
\begin{itemize}
    \item\small For a better understanding we might consider the weather conditions in the period 2019-2023 (one year prior to our analysis).
    \item\small Datas were taken from Agenzia Lucana di Sviluppo e di Innovazione in Agricoltura:
    \item\url{https://www.alsia.it/opencms/opencms/Temi/attivita/Report-climatici-annuali/}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Discussion}
Generally in these areas rainfalls are concentrated in autumn and spring, while summer is pretty dry. 
    \begin{itemize}
        \item\small \textbf{2019}: was characterized buy various hails and storms events, especially in the \textbf{spring/summer} period, this may have affected the vegetation in the following months; \textbf{autumn} was pretty hot and dry.
        \vspace{2mm}
        \item\small \textbf{2020}: characterized by an \textbf{extremely dry winter}; some precipitation during the \textbf{spring/summer period,} but also a hot and very dry \textbf{autumn} until mid-November.
        \vspace{2mm}
        \item\small \textbf{2021}: numerous heat waves during \textbf{summer}, warm and partly dry \textbf{winter}; as well as a dry \textbf{spring};
    \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Discussion}
    \begin{itemize}
         \item\small \textbf{2022}: similar pattern of 2021
         \vspace{2mm}
        \item\small \textbf{2023}:\textbf{ mild, shorter and mostly dry winter} (in January 8.5° of mean T was recorded, compared to 4.4° of 2019); cool, unstable and \textbf{very rainy spring}; \textbf{very hot and dry summer} with numerous heat waves; \textbf{hot and very dry autumn}.
    \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Conclusion}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \small It seems that in the Murgia areas considered, the Fraction of Vegetation Cover and the NDVI index has increased from 2020 to 2023, suggesting an \textbf{improvement} of the extent of green vegetations as well as its density and health.
    \item \small It would be interesting to understand the \textbf{species composition changes} that is occurring in the area, since climate change is expected to have significant impacts on it and also on ecosystem structure and distribution. The vegetation types in these areas range from forests to woodlands, savannas, shrublands, and grasslands.
    \item \small With increasing temperatures and decreased precipitation, generally an expansion of \textbf{scrublands and shrublands} will be favoured, at the expense of \textbf{forests} (important habitats for Falco naumanni) or \textbf{grasslands}.
    \item \small However, the Mediterranean scrub has greater phenotypic plasticity, which allows it to adapt to current conditions with fewer problems. Added to this is the ability of the bushes to colonize the soil in extreme conditions, such as after a fire or during a dry period.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Conclusion}
\begin{itemize}
    \item\small However, climate change is having significant \textbf{impacts on agricultural systems} and cultivated landscapes in the region.
    \item\small There are documented widespread critical issues related to \textbf{root asphyxiation} and \textbf{fruit splitting }(cracking). In the case of cereals there were evident \textbf{quality problems}, as well as \textbf{phytosanitary} ones, while for vegetable transplants there were delays due to frequent rains.
    \item\small Due to the prolonged drought, even the non-irrigated olive tree was put to the test. In fact, the small amount of cold accumulated so far is creating some concern about a probable \textbf{early awakening or failure to satisfy the physiological needs}, at least for the most demanding species.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

